title: [ROCm] Share CUDA IsAllFinite kernel
body:
**Description**:
1.  Delete ROCm's IsAllFinite kernel, reuse the CUDA version (used via AMD Hipify).
2.  Add type inferencing for IsAllFinite's output (scalar bool), and update the shape to match in optimizer builder.
3.  IsAllFinite output doesn't need to explicitly be listed as CPU output - if onnxruntime decides the output needs to be used by CPU, then it will insert a MemcpyToHost node.  This also eliminates the need for a (1-byte) scratch buffer.

**Motivation and Context**
The goal is to reuse as much code as possible between CUDA and ROCm, as long as there's no performance or functional reason for diverging.  In this case, there's no measurable performance difference.

title: Refactor implementation of Tensor<T> and underlying buffer stores to improve binary size and maintainability
body:
Refactor implementation of Tensor<T> and underlying buffer stores to improve binary size and maintainability

TensorBuffer<T> has been refactored into an inheritance model and the root "buffer" noun has been changed to "data"
The new inheritance model is based on idata as the root interface, and the numeric_data implementation for all numeric tensors, and string_data implementation for string tensors.

The Tensor<T> type has been delegates to one of the 2 implementatoins, and so the number of different backing buffer (data) implementations in the binary should reduce from #of tensor data types to 2.

title: Add QLinearConv NHWC transformer
body:
**Description**: The implementation of QLinearConv internally does a transpose(NHWC)->im2col+GEMM->transpose(NCHW). This adds a graph transformer to change a model to use a com.microsoft.QLinearConv that supports NHWC natively to avoid unnecessary transposes.

**Motivation and Context**:
This improves inferencing performance by canceling out unnecessary transposes. On a Broadwell class system, a mobilenetv3 model goes from 9.5ms->7.5ms, and a resnet50 model goes from 29.5ms->25.5ms. Worst case, the transformer adds the same number of Transpose operations that the graph was already running without the transformer.

Added a com.microsoft.QLinearConv op that has an extra channels_last attribute. The kernel implementation is fused with the ONNX version of the operator.

There is a new extended optimization (-o 99) transformer modeled on the NCHWc transformer. This rewrites the graph to use the com.microsoft.QLinearConv operator and inserts Transpose nodes to switch formats. QLinearAdd/QLinearMul can stay in channels last format if both inputs are channels last. QLinearSigmoid/QLinearLeakyRelu can also handle either format of tensor. The transformer handles 1D/2D/ND tensors.

The CPU EP version of Transpose calls MlasTranspose in the path used for NCHW/NHWC simple transposes.

title: Cache build docker images in container registry.
body:
**Description**
This PR adds infrastructure to automatically cache docker images used in CI builds in a container registry.

Currently, build images are pulled from a container registry for some builds and built every time for others. The container registry requires maintenance to keep the images up to date and building images every time wastes build agent resources.

With this change, a given build image can be looked up in a cache container registry and if present, pulled, and otherwise, built and pushed. The uniqueness of a build image is determined by a hash digest of the dockerfile, docker build context directory, and certain "docker build" options. This digest is part of the image tag in the cache container repository.

The cache container registry will need to be cleaned up periodically. This is not automated yet.

**Motivation and Context**
Reduce maintenance of existing build docker images in container registry. Reduce build times for builds which always rebuild their docker image.

title: Enable direct tensorization and detensorization to many buffers in WinML
body:
Enable direct tensorization and detensorization to many buffers in WinML

Callers into WinML can sometimes have data spread into multiple cpu buffers, or want to use a batched api call with data spread across multiple cpu buffers. In doing so, the engine currently requires callers to copy their buffers into a single contiguous block of memory before invoking the WinML API.
1) This is inconvenient.
2) For GPU evaluation, a contiguous buffer of memory is not required, as multiple buffers can be copied into a single GPU resource without needing to allocate another copy of the memory.

This change allows efficient upload and concatentation of tensors when specified via multiple buffers inputs.

title: Inputs with UINT8 should fallback to CUDA instead of failing to compile with TRT execution provider

labels.name: type:enhancement
labels.description: request for unsupported feature or enhancement

body:
Models with uint8 inputs are not supported by TRT execution provider. This is fine, but the node should fallback to CUDA, instead of failing to to the conversion in onnxruntime.


**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using):
1.5.2

**Describe the solution you'd like**
In my case the first operation in the model is a cast to fp32 anyway, according to the onnx profiler this costs  **0.01ms** on CUDA.
Compared to doing this cast on a 512x616 grayscale image on the caller side before:
**Python**(numpy astype): **0.8ms**
**C#** (static array definition and copy with BlockCopy): **1ms**

Also int8 is not really an alternative, images/data that is received, either overflows are needs to be shifted, which also costs 0.65ms in python. Furthermore it needs retraining/further changes on the model (correct me if there is a smarter way).

Hence, just executing this operatoin in CUDA should be cheaper, either by beeing able to mark some operations to force them to run on a defined executor, or just hardcode it for this kind of casts.
**Describe alternatives you've considered**
A clear and concise description of any alternative solutions or features you've considered.

**Additional context**
Tested on Nvidia T4/Quadro Intel and AMD CPUs

title: Support EPs that compile nodes in a minimal build.
body:
**Description**: 
Add support for EPs that compile nodes in a minimal build. This will enable the NNAPI EP to be used at runtime with an ORT format model.
  - add 'extended' minimal build that pulls in the infrastructure required to compile a node at runtime
    - there is a non-trivial amount of infrastructure required, so separating from the base minimal build where users may not want to pay the binary size price for features they do not need.
  - add ability to create compiled node without creating a new Model instance
    - creating a Model would result in pulling in all the Graph code, so we use a GraphViewer for the set of nodes to be compiled.
  - update graph partitioning to enable creating an ORT format model where nodes may be taken by a compiling EP, and to work in a minimal build with an ORT format model
  - provide mechanism to fallback to CPU EP for nodes that are not handled at runtime by a compiling EP
    - when creating the ORT format model the compiling EP provides information on the nodes it could potentially handle. we do not do further optimizations on those nodes so that they're guaranteed to be available to the compiling EP and included in the required kernels when creating the minimal build. at runtime the compiling EP may not be available, or the device may have limited support, so fewer nodes may be taken by the EP. in that case we use the CPU EP to execute any left over nodes. 
  - add test EP that can be used to unit test the behavior
    - compiling EPs tend to be device/hardware specific so having a CPU based EP that replicates the functionality makes testing significantly easier

**Motivation and Context**
Enable using NNAPI on device with an ORT format model.

body:
I converted the yolov5s model to onnx, and used onnxruntime for forward calculation. When I use the onnxruntime cpu version, everything is ok, but when use onnxruntime-gpu, the same input occasionally has different output.

**System information**
- windows10/centos7
- https://pypi.tuna.tsinghua.edu.cn/simple `pip install onnxruntime-gpu` 
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.4.0/1.5.2
- Python version: 3.7.6
- CUDA/cuDNN version: cuda10.1
- GPU: RTX2070/RTX2080TI 

**code and model**
[model](https://drive.google.com/file/d/11PF5HpCes6LfwZ2qhJjnTVZNaiKUv_vz/view?usp=sharing)
[test image](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1brLpwYqILO23hJP_A88XTR7jjXZZDg4Y/view?usp=sharing)

```python
import cv2
import numpy as np
import onnxruntime

def letterbox(img, new_shape=(640, 640), color=(114, 114, 114), auto=True, scaleFill=False, scaleup=True):
    # Resize image to a 32-pixel-multiple rectangle https://github.com/ultralytics/yolov3/issues/232
    shape = img.shape[:2]  # current shape [height, width]
    if isinstance(new_shape, int):
        new_shape = (new_shape, new_shape)

    # Scale ratio (new / old)
    r = min(new_shape[0] / shape[0], new_shape[1] / shape[1])
    if not scaleup:  # only scale down, do not scale up (for better test mAP)
        r = min(r, 1.0)

    # Compute padding
    ratio_w, ratio_h = r, r  # width, height ratios
    new_unpad = int(round(shape[1] * r)), int(round(shape[0] * r))
    dw, dh = new_shape[1] - new_unpad[0], new_shape[0] - new_unpad[1]  # wh padding
    # pdb.set_trace()
    if auto:  # minimum rectangle
        dw, dh = np.mod(dw, 64), np.mod(dh, 64)  # wh padding
    elif scaleFill:  # stretch
        dw, dh = 0.0, 0.0
        new_unpad = (new_shape[1], new_shape[0])
        ratio_w, ratio_h = new_shape[1] / shape[1], new_shape[0] / shape[0]  # width, height ratios

    dw /= 2  # divide padding into 2 sides
    dh /= 2

    if shape[::-1] != new_unpad:  # resize
        img = cv2.resize(img, new_unpad, interpolation=cv2.INTER_LINEAR)
    top, bottom = int(round(dh - 0.1)), int(round(dh + 0.1))
    left, right = int(round(dw - 0.1)), int(round(dw + 0.1))
    img = cv2.copyMakeBorder(img, top, bottom, left, right, cv2.BORDER_CONSTANT, value=color)  # add border
    return img, ratio_w, ratio_h, dw, dh



class Detection:
    def __init__(self, model_path, names, prob_threshold=0.6, iou_threshold=0.5, debug=False):
        # onnxruntime
        so = onnxruntime.SessionOptions()
        so.graph_optimization_level = onnxruntime.GraphOptimizationLevel.ORT_ENABLE_BASIC # ORT_ENABLE_EXTENDED ORT_ENABLE_ALL
        so.intra_op_num_threads = 4
        so.execution_mode = onnxruntime.ExecutionMode.ORT_SEQUENTIAL # ORT_PARALLEL ORT_SEQUENTIAL
        self.ort_session = onnxruntime.InferenceSession(model_path, sess_options=so)              
        _, self.net_input_channels, self.net_input_height, self.net_input_width = self.ort_session.get_inputs()[0].shape

        # param
        self.prob_threshold = prob_threshold
        self.iou_threshold = iou_threshold
        self.debug = debug
        self.names = names

    def prepare_image(self, image):
        image_scaled, ratio_w, ratio_h, dw, dh = letterbox(image, new_shape=(self.net_input_width, self.net_input_height), auto=False, scaleFill=False, scaleup=True)
        image_scaled = image_scaled[:, :, ::-1].transpose(2, 0, 1)  # BGR to RGB 
        image_scaled = image_scaled[np.newaxis, ...]
        image_scaled = np.ascontiguousarray(image_scaled)
        image_scaled = image_scaled.astype(np.float32) / 255.0

        return image_scaled, ratio_w, ratio_h, dw, dh

    def forward(self, image):
        # prepare image
        image_input, ratio_w, ratio_h, dw, dh = self.prepare_image(image)

        # inference
        ort_inputs = {self.ort_session.get_inputs()[0].name: image_input}
        output_name = self.ort_session.get_outputs()[0].name
        ort_outs = self.ort_session.run([output_name], ort_inputs)
        
        # post process
        pred = ort_outs[0]
        print(pred.sum())
        # result = self.post_process(pred, image.shape, ratio_w, ratio_h, dw, dh)
        # dets = result[0]

        return pred 


if __name__ == "__main__":
``` 
